Question 1

Researchers are interested in the relationship of demographic factors and alcohol consumption on cirrhosis death rates. You have been given a dataset containing population, drinking data, and cirrhosis death rates for 46 US states in the data/wine_data.txt file. The variables of interest are:

  • urban_pop the percentage of urban population in the state

  • late_births a measure of the number of births to women between 45 to 49

  • wine_consumption the consumption of wine per capita

  • liquor_consumption the consumption of hard liquor per capita

  • cirrhosis_death the death rate from cirrhosis (outcome)

a)

Read the data into your environment using the read_table2() function. Take a look at the original data file and describe its format. Explain why we needed to use the read_table2() function you can take a look at the help file for read_table2() for help.

wine_data <- read_table2("data/wine_data.txt")

b)

Create scatterplots that display the relationship between each continuous variable (urban_pop, late_births, wine_consumption, and liquor_consumption) with the dependent variable of interest cirrhosis_death.

Make sure to add a proper title to each graph, and descriptive titles to the x and y axes (not just the variable names).

Based on these scatterplots, which continuous independent variables have a linear relationship with cirrhosis_death? Please answer in a sentence.

ggplot(data = wine_data) +
  geom_point(aes(x = urban_pop, y = cirrhosis_death)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Percent Urban Population by Cirrhosis Death Rates", 
       x = "Percent Urban Population", y = "Cirrhosis Death Rates")

ggplot(data = wine_data) +
  geom_point(aes(x = late_births, y = cirrhosis_death)) +
  theme_bw() +

       x = "Late Births", y = "Cirrhosis Death Rates")

ggplot(data = wine_data) +

ggplot(data = wine_data) +

  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Liquor Consumption by Cirrhosis Death Rates", 
       x = "Liquor Consumption", y = "Cirrhosis Death Rates")

Answer:

Based on these scatter plots, urban population, late births, wine consumption, and liquor consumption all look like they could have a linear relationship with cirrhosis death rate.

d)

Question 2

You have been given a small data file of the average weight (in pounds) for two strains of guinea pig from a series of years in the early 20th century. This data is stored in data/gpig_dat.csv and has a variable for year and a variable for each strain. The value in each cell of the strain variable is the weight for that strain in that year.

a)

Graph guinea pig weights by year in a line plot (using both line and point geoms).

For your graph: (1) Each strain should be a different color and a different line type. For the color, dont use default R choices, but choose your own custom colors. (2) The background of your plot should be white, not the default gray. (3) Your graph should have a title, and the x and y axes should also have titles (not just the variable names). (4) The legend should have a title and should be at the top of your graph.

gpig_dat <- read_csv("data/gpig_dat.csv") %>%
  janitor::clean_names()

gpig_long <- gpig_dat %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = 2:3,
               names_to = "strain",
               values_to = "weight")

ggplot(data = gpig_long) +
  geom_point(aes(x = year, y = weight, color = factor(strain))) +
  geom_line(aes(x = year, y = weight, color = factor(strain), linetype = factor(strain))) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Guinea Pig Weights over Time by Strain", x = "Year", y = "Weight", color = "Strain", linetype = "Strain") +
  theme(legend.position = "top") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("strain_13" = "forestgreen", "strain_b" = "darkred"))

b)

Use a two-sample t-test to test the hypothesis that mean guinea pig weights are equal, at a two-sided level of significance of 5%. Use tidy() and kable() functions to provide the summary results of your t-test and also report the test statistic, degrees of freedom, and p-value in a sentence that explains whether you reject or do not reject the null hypothesis.

t_res <- t.test(weight ~ strain, data = gpig_long)

clean_res <- tidy(t_res)

kable(clean_res)
estimate estimate1 estimate2 statistic p.value parameter conf.low conf.high method alternative
-0.1055556 2.645556 2.751111 -1.135204 0.2734787 15.5563 -0.3031303 0.0920192 Welch Two Sample t-test two.sided 
tstat <- clean_res$statistic

t_par <- clean_res$parameter

t_pval <- clean_res$p.value

Answer:

The data do not provide enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that mean guinea pig weights are different between the two strains at a level of significance of 5%. The t-statistic was -1.1352037 with 15.5562965 degrees of freedom and a p-value of 0.2734787.

c)

Use a permutation test to test whether the minimum weight of guinea pigs are equal between strains, at a two-sided level of significance of 5%. Your permutation test should simulate at least 2000 test statistics.*

In your solution, be sure to (1) provide a histogram of simulated test statistics with your observed statistic clearly marked, and (2) include a final interpretation sentence that reports your test p-value and decision to reject or not reject the null hypothesis.

calculate_ts <- function(df){
  summary <- df %>% 
    group_by(strain) %>%
    summarize(min_weight = min(weight))

  strain_b_med <- summary %>%
    filter(strain == "strain_b") %>%
    pull(min_weight)
  
  strain_13_med <- summary %>%
    filter(strain == "strain_13") %>%
    pull(min_weight)
  
  difference <- strain_b_med - strain_13_med
  return(difference)
}

obs_stat <- calculate_ts(gpig_long)

#permutation function
perform_permutation <- function(df){
  permuted <- df %>%
    mutate(weight = sample(weight))
  return(permuted)
}

#get permuted test statistic
get_permuted_ts <- function(df){
  permed <- perform_permutation(df)
  ts <- calculate_ts(permed)
  return(ts)
}

#perform all permutations
results <- map_dbl(1:2000, function(x) get_permuted_ts(gpig_long))

#plot results
res_tibble <- tibble(sim_stat = results)

ggplot(data = res_tibble) +
  geom_histogram(aes(x = sim_stat), 
                 bins = 30, fill = "blue", color = "white") + 
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = obs_stat), linetype = "dashed") +
  theme_bw()

p_value <- res_tibble %>%
  mutate(abs_val_greater = if_else(abs(sim_stat) >= abs(obs_stat), 1, 0)) %>%
  group_by(abs_val_greater) %>%
  summarize(n = n()) %>%
  mutate(proportion = n/sum(n)) %>%
  filter(abs_val_greater == 1) %>%
  pull(proportion)

Answer:

The data do not provide enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that mean guinea pig weights are different between the two strains at a level of significance of 5% (p-value = 0.215).

Question 3

You have been given six datasets with repeated measures of MIRECC GAF Social Functioning scores for an observational study of individuals with schizophrenia. Each dataset includes a GAF SF measurement at a different follow-up visit. These files are stored in the data/gaf_files folder.

a)

Combine all six datasets using a method that will remove any individuals who are not present in ALL datasets.

baseline <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_1.csv")
v2 <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_2.csv")
v3 <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_3.csv")
v4 <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_4.csv")
v5 <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_5.csv")
v6 <- read_csv("data/gaf_files/visit_6.csv")

total_joined <- baseline %>%
  inner_join(v2, by = c("patient_id" = "id")) %>%
  inner_join(v3, by = c("patient_id" = "study_id")) %>%
  inner_join(v4, by = c("patient_id" = "study_id")) %>%
  inner_join(v5, by = "patient_id") %>%
  inner_join(v6, by = c("patient_id" = "id"))

b)

Reproduce the graph shown in the gaf_plot.png file as closely as you can. You can see this file by clicking on it in your file explorer. Notice that the graph is faceted by site and has the mean values and their confidence interval overlaid on each plot in red.

long_data <- total_joined %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("visit"),
               names_to = "visit",
               values_to = "gaf_sf")


mean_summary <- long_data %>%
  group_by(site, visit) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(gaf_sf),
            sd = sd(gaf_sf),
            n = n(),
            upper = mean + 1.96*sd/sqrt(n),
            lower = mean - 1.96*sd/sqrt(n))


ggplot(data = long_data) +
  geom_line(aes(x = visit, y = gaf_sf, group = factor(patient_id)), alpha = 0.4) +
  theme_bw() +
  geom_pointrange(data = mean_summary, aes(x = visit, y = mean, ymax = upper, ymin = lower), color = "red", size = 0.5) +
  facet_wrap(~factor(site)) +
  labs(title = "GAF Social Functioning by Site", x = "Visit", y = "GAF SF") +
  scale_x_discrete(labels = 1:6)
